<html>
  <head>
    <meta http-equiv="content-type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8">
    <title>Management plan</title>
    <link id="light-styles" rel="stylesheet" href="Case_sheet_styles.css">
    <link id="dark-styles" rel="alternate stylesheet" title="dark" href="Case_sheet_styles_dark.css">
  </head>
  <body> <button id="theme-toggle" title="Toggle dark mode">🌙 Dark Mode</button>
    <h3 class="General">MANAGEMENT PLAN</h3>
    <h4 class="General">OBO Urgency</h4>
    <ul>
      <li class="General">Explain why are we going with each of these options?</li>
      <li class="General">Urgent Admission:
        <ol class="General">
          <li class="SOB respiratory emergency">Acute severe shortness of breath
            / Respiratory distress</li>
          <li class="chest-pain emergency cvs">Suspected Acute Coronary Syndrome
            (ACS), PE, Aortic Dissection</li>
          <li class="palpitations cvs emergency">Palpitations with adverse
            features (syncope, chest pain, severe SOB, hypotension)</li>
          <li class="PAD cvs emergency">Acute Limb Ischaemia (6 P's: Pain,
            Pallor, Pulselessness, Paresthesia, Paralysis, Perishingly cold)</li>
          <li class="cough respiratory emergency">Cough with significant
            hemoptysis, severe respiratory distress, or signs of severe
            pneumonia</li>
          <li class="Herpes-Zoster infectious cns emergency">Complicated Zoster
            (e.g., Ophthalmic, Ramsay Hunt, Disseminated, Immunocompromised
            patient)</li>
          <li class="General">systemic, or</li>
          <li class="ent">mastoiditis</li>
          <li class="ent">TIA ...all with out ot with abcd score....24 hrs</li>
          <li class="headache cns emergency">Sudden-onset severe "thunderclap"
            headache, or headache with fever/neck stiffness, new neurological
            deficit, or reduced consciousness</li>
          <li class="ms cns emergency">Acute MS relapse with significant
            disability (e.g., severe visual loss, motor impairment preventing
            self-care)</li>
          <li class="sinusitis ent cns emergency">Signs of complicated sinusitis
            (periorbital swelling/erythema, displaced globe, severe headache,
            signs of meningitis, focal neurology)</li>
          <li class="iih cns emergency ophthalmology">Signs of severe
            Intracranial Hypertension (e.g., altered consciousness, significant
            visual loss, signs of herniation)</li>
        </ol>
      </li>
      <li class="General">Urgent Referral (2 weeks):
        <ol class="General">
          <li class="OSA respiratory cns ent">Suspected severe OSA with
            significant daytime somnolence, especially in high-risk occupations
            (e.g., commercial drivers)</li>
          <li class="chest-pain cvs">Stable chest pain with concerning features
            (for Rapid Access Clinic)</li>
          <li class="Herpes-Zoster ophthalmology">Urgent same-day ophthalmology
            referral for suspected Zoster Ophthalmicus</li>
          <li class="PAD cvs surgery">Critical Limb Ischaemia (rest pain &gt; 2
            weeks, ulceration, or gangrene) - refer to vascular surgery</li>
          <li class="cough respiratory oncology"> cough &gt; 3 weeks (or just
            hemoptysis) in &gt; 40 yrs with risk factors (e.g., smoking) - for
            CXR/Cancer pathway</li>
          <li class=" ent">Recurrent AOM, treatment failure, or</li>
          <li class="General ">complications</li>
          <li class="cns ">First seizure - first seizure clinic!</li>
          <li class="headache rheumatic ophthalmology">Suspected Giant Cell
            Arteritis (GCA) - same day referral to rheumatology/ophthalmology</li>
          <li class="ms cns">Suspected first presentation of demyelination (to
            Neurology)</li>
          <li class="sinusitis ent cns">Chronic or recurrent sinusitis failing
            primary care treatment</li>
          <li class="iih cns ophthalmology">Suspected new case of IIH (e.g.,
            headache with papilledema) for urgent Neurology and Ophthalmology
            assessment</li>
        </ol>
      </li>
      <li class="General">Routine Referral:
        <ol class="General">
          <li class="OSA respiratory ent">Suspected OSA based on screening
            questionnaires (e.g., Epworth, STOP-BANG)</li>
          <li class="ent">Recurrent AOM (&ge;3 episodes in 6 months or &ge;4 in
            12 months)</li>
          <li class="palpitations cvs">Recurrent unexplained or bothersome
            palpitations</li>
          <li class="PAD cvs">Intermittent claudication with lifestyle-limiting
            symptoms for consideration of supervised exercise/revascularisation</li>
        </ol>
      </li>
      <li class="General">Handling In-House:
        <ol class="General">
          <li class="ent">Uncomplicated AOM</li>
        </ol>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <h4 class="General">Patient-Specific Plan</h4>
    <ol>
      <li class="General">Want someone to listen in? (Patient partnership)</li>
      <li class="emergency">family coming?</li>
      <ol class="General">
        <li>do you want any family ...especially for learning disability or</li>
        <li>for other diability </li>
        <li class="General">we can call ..... for you</li>
      </ol>
      <li class="General">Assess Mental Capacity (if any doubt about
        decision-making ability)</li>
      <li class="General"><b>Safeguarding </b>issues (adult/child protection
        concerns)</li>
      <li class="General">Initial <b>Investigations</b>
        <ul>
          <li class="General">Screening Questionnaires:
            <ul>
              <li class="OSA cns ent">Epworth Sleepiness Scale (ESS)</li>
              <li class="OSA cns ent">STOP-BANG questionnaire</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li class="General"><em>Consent (ensure informed, check understanding)</em></li>
          <li class="iih cns ophthalmology">Urgent Fundoscopy (check for
            papilledema)</li>
          <li class="iih cns ophthalmology">Formal Visual Field Assessment &amp;
            Visual Acuity</li>
          <li class="iih cns">Blood Pressure</li>
          <li class="palpitations cvs">ECG (12-lead), check for long QT, delta
            waves (WPW)</li>
          <li class="PAD cvs">Ankle-Brachial Pressure Index (ABPI)</li>
          <li class="SOB respiratory">Pulse oximetry (SpO2)</li>
          <li class="cough respiratory">Sputum sample (if purulent or for TB
            culture)</li>
          <li class="Herpes-Zoster infectious">Viral swab for atypical
            presentations</li>
          <li class="chest-pain cvs">ECG (12-lead, within 10 mins of arrival for
            chest pain)</li>
          <li class="General">Blood work: </li>
          <ul>
            <li class="chest-pain cvs">Troponin (serial if indicated), FBC,
              U&amp;E, LFTs, Lipids, Hba1c</li>
            <li class="chest-pain cvs">D-dimer (if low suspicion of PE)</li>
            <li class="SOB cvs">BNP (B-type natriuretic peptide) if suspecting
              heart failure</li>
            <li class="palpitations cvs endocrine">Thyroid Function Tests
              (TFTs), check electrolytes</li>
            <li class="PAD cvs endocrine">HbA1c, Lipid profile</li>
            <li class="headache rheumatic">ESR/CRP (if suspecting Giant Cell
              Arteritis)</li>
            <li class="surgery urology">Prostate specific antigen</li>
            <li class="surgery urology">Tumor markers at specialist</li>
            <ul>
              <li class="surgery urology">AFP</li>
              <li class="surgery urology">HCG</li>
              <li class="surgery urology">LDH</li>
            </ul>
          </ul>
          <li class="General">Imaging:
            <ul>
              <li class="nephro urology">Urine dip stick</li>
              <li class="chest-pain cvs respiratory SOB cough">Chest X-ray (CXR)
                - essential for persistent cough or red flags</li>
              <li class="hematology">Multiple myeloma</li>
              <li class="cns respiratory">MRI</li>
              <li class="iih cns">MRI Brain + MR Venography (MRV) - essential to
                rule out structural causes and venous sinus thrombosis.</li>
              <li class="iih cns emergency">CT Head first if suspecting acute
                bleed or major structural shift.</li>
              <li class="headache cns">CT/MRI Head (Indicated for red flag
                headaches, not typically for uncomplicated primary headaches)</li>
              <li class="ms cns">MRI Brain &amp; Spine (with contrast)</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li class="PAD cvs surgery">Duplex Ultrasound / CT or MR Angiography
            (for revascularisation planning)</li>
          <li class="chest-pain cvs emergency">CT Pulmonary Angiogram (CTPA) or
            V/Q scan for PE</li>
          <li class="SOB cvs">Echocardiogram (for heart failure, structural
            disease)</li>
          <li class="cns respiratory">CT Scan</li>
          <ul class="nephro urology">
            <li class="nephro urology">Renal stones</li>
          </ul>
          <li class="sinusitis ent cns">Sinusitis: Generally no imaging needed
            for acute, uncomplicated cases</li>
          <li class="sinusitis ent cns">CT sinuses (for chronic sinusitis or
            suspected complications)</li>
          <li class="sinusitis ent cns">CO headache -investigate in children and
            pregnants</li>
          <li class="respiratory general">Ultrasound</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li class="ms cns">Specialized tests:
        <ul>
          <li class="ms cns">Lumbar Puncture (for CSF oligoclonal bands)</li>
          <li class="ms ophthalmology">Visual Evoked Potentials (VEPs)</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li class="SOB respiratory">Lung Function Tests:
        <ul>
          <li class="SOB respiratory">Spirometry (FEV1/FVC ratio)</li>
          <li class="SOB respiratory">Peak flow diary</li>
          <li class="cough respiratory">Bronchial challenge test (e.g.,
            methacholine) if asthma is suspected but spirometry is normal</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li class="derma">Dermoscopy</li>
      <li class="derma">Photography</li>
      <li class="General">Biopsy:
        <ul>
          <li>Excisional biopsy - we dont sample biopsy
            <ul>
              <li class="derma">Mole suspect</li>
              <li class="derma">BCC</li>
              <li class="derma">SCC</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li>if positive then wide excision</li>
          <li><em>ADR</em> = <em>Complications</em>
            <ul>
              <li class="derma">bleeding</li>
              <li class="derma">infection</li>
              <li class="derma">pain</li>
              <li class="derma">scarring</li>
              <li class="derma">disfigurement</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li class="General ">Further Investigations</li>
      <ul class="General">
        <li class="General cvs">Specialized tests: </li>
        <ul class="surgery urology">
          <li class="OSA respiratory ent">Overnight sleep study (Polysomnography
            or home oximetry)</li>
          <li class="surgery urology">Cystoscope</li>
          <li class="iih cns">Lumbar Puncture with opening pressure measurement
            (ONLY after imaging has excluded a mass lesion).</li>
          <li class="palpitations cvs">Ambulatory ECG (e.g., 24/48-hr Holter
            monitor, event recorder)</li>
          <li class="surgery">biopsy</li>
        </ul>
        <li class="General">Referrals: </li>
      </ul>
    </ol>
    <ol class="General">
      <li class="General">EXPLAIN FINDINGS</li>
      <ul>
        <li class="ortho-specific">Explain realistic recovery timeline (e.g.,
          sprains may take weeks to heal, not days)</li>
        <li class="Herpes-Zoster">Explain shingles diagnosis, link to chickenpox
          virus, risk of PHN</li>
        <li class="sinusitis ent cns">Acute Viral Rhinosinusitis</li>
        <li class="sinusitis ent infectious cns">Acute Bacterial Rhinosinusitis</li>
        <li class="sinusitis ent cns">Chronic Rhinosinusitis (with or without
          polyps)</li>
        <li class="ms cns">Explain MS diagnosis, chronic autoimmune condition
          affecting the central nervous system, and its variable course</li>
        <li class="General">Acknowledge and explain diagnostic uncertainty if
          present</li>
      </ul>
      <li>ICE : Ideas, Concerns, Expectations
        <ol>
          <li>Ideas</li>
          <li>Concerns
            <ul>
              <li class="SOB">Fear of suffocating / inability to breathe</li>
              <li>loss of function</li>
              <li>need for a treatment option</li>
              <li>recurrence</li>
              <li>loss of work</li>
              <li>discomfort</li>
              <li>disfigurement</li>
              <li>scarring</li>
              <li>cancer</li>
              <li class="Herpes-Zoster">Persistent pain (Post-Herpetic
                Neuralgia)</li>
              <li class="ms cns">Fear of disability progression</li>
              <li class="ms cns">Impact on career and family</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li>Expectations
            <ul>
              <li>treatment options</li>
              <li>expected course</li>
              <li>and warning signs</li>
              <li class="General">Discuss treatment burden (impact of the plan
                on the patient's life)</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </li>
      <li class="General"><strong>PROVISIONAL DIAGNOSIS:</strong></li>
      <ol class="General">
        <li class="General">ANATOMICAL: </li>
        <ul>
          <li class="ent">middle ear</li>
          <li class="headache cns">Headache disorders</li>
        </ul>
        <li class="General">ETIOLOGICAL:
          <ul class="General infectious">
            <li class="General infectious">Bacterial (S. pneumoniae, H.
              influenzae, M. catarrhalis)</li>
            <li class="General infectious">viral</li>
            <li class="Herpes-Zoster infectious">Varicella-Zoster Virus (VZV)
              Reactivation</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li class="General">ETIOLOGICAL:
          <ul class="General infectious">
            <li class="General infectious">Bacterial (S. pneumoniae, H.
              influenzae, M. catarrhalis)</li>
            <li class="General infectious">viral</li>
            <li class="Herpes-Zoster infectious">Varicella-Zoster Virus (VZV)
              Reactivation</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li class="General">PATHOLOGICAL:</li>
        <ul>
          <li class="ent">Acute inflammation with middle ear effusion</li>
          <li class="SOB respiratory">Bronchoconstriction / Airway inflammation</li>
        </ul>
        <li class="General">CLINICAL:</li>
        <ul>
          <li class="ent">Acute Otitis Media (AOM) - [Mild/Moderate/Severe]</li>
          <li class="Herpes-Zoster infectious">Herpes Zoster (Shingles) -
            specify dermatome (e.g., T4)</li>
          <li class="SOB respiratory">Asthma Exacerbation / COPD Exacerbation</li>
          <li class="cough respiratory">Acute Bronchitis (viral)</li>
          <li class="cough respiratory infectious">Community-Acquired Pneumonia</li>
          <li class="cough respiratory">Post-viral cough</li>
          <li class="cough git">Gastro-oesophageal Reflux Disease (GORD)-related
            cough</li>
          <li class="cough ent">Upper Airway Cough Syndrome (Post-nasal drip)</li>
          <li class="OSA respiratory">Obstructive Sleep Apnoea (OSA) -
            [Mild/Moderate/Severe] based on AHI</li>
          <li class="SOB cvs">Acute Heart Failure Exacerbation</li>
          <li class="iih cns">Idiopathic Intracranial Hypertension (IIH)</li>
          <li class="iih cns">Secondary Intracranial Hypertension (specify cause
            if known)</li>
        </ul>
      </ol>
      <li class=" h4 General">Treatment Plan </li>
      <li><b>Seniors </b>: Almost always we will involve the seniors</li>
      <li class="General">Shared Decision-Making
        <ul>
          <li>Discuss options, risks, benefits, and reasonable alternatives
            (including no treatment)</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li class="General"><b>Symptomatic </b>treatment:
        <ul class="General">
          <li class="General">Analgesia:
            <ol>
              <li class="ortho-specific">Check for contraindications (allergies,
                gastritis, asthma) and current medications</li>
              <li>Paracetamol 15mg/kg/dose Q4-6H PRN (max 4g/day) or</li>
              <li>Ibuprofen 10mg/kg/dose Q6-8H PRN</li>
              <li class="chest-pain cvs">GTN spray/tablets PRN for stable angina
                (counsel on use)</li>
              <li class="ortho-specific">Advise on escalation: e.g., paracetamol
                first, +/- topical NSAID, then oral NSAID if needed</li>
              <li class="Herpes-Zoster cns">Consider neuropathic pain ladder
                (e.g., Amitriptyline, Gabapentin for PHN)</li>
              <li>gastroprotection </li>
              <li>omeprazole 20mg PO daily</li>
            </ol>
          </li>
          <li class="General">Topical analgesia: </li>
          <ol>
            <li class="ent">Antipyrine-benzocaine otic drops if TM intact</li>
          </ol>
          <li class="respiratory ent">Nasal decongestants: </li>
          <ol>
            <li class="respiratory ent">Consider in children &gt;12 years and
              adults (e.g., oxymetazoline 0.05% 2-3 sprays per nostril BID for
              &le;3 days)</li>
          </ol>
          <li class="SOB respiratory">Immediate relief for SOB:
            <ol>
              <li class="SOB">Positioning (upright, tripod position)</li>
              <li class="SOB respiratory">Oxygen therapy to target saturations
                (e.g., 94-98% or 88-92% in COPD)</li>
            </ol>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li class="General">Specific treatment:
        <ul class="SOB respiratory">
          <li class="SOB respiratory"><b>Asthma/COPD Exacerbation:</b></li>
          <ol>
            <li class="SOB respiratory">Bronchodilators (e.g., Salbutamol via
              nebulizer/spacer)</li>
            <li class="SOB respiratory">Systemic Corticosteroids (e.g.,
              Prednisolone)</li>
            <li class="SOB respiratory">Antibiotics if evidence of infection</li>
            <li class="SOB respiratory">Check and correct inhaler technique</li>
          </ol>
          <li class="SOB cvs"><b>Acute Heart Failure:</b></li>
          <ol>
            <li class="SOB cvs">Diuretics (e.g., IV Furosemide)</li>
            <li class="SOB cvs">Vasodilators (e.g., GTN)</li>
          </ol>
        </ul>
        <ul class="Herpes-Zoster infectious pharmacology">
          <li class="Herpes-Zoster"><b>Antiviral Therapy for Zoster:</b></li>
          <ol>
            <li class="Herpes-Zoster">Offer if within 72h of rash onset
              (especially if age &gt;50, severe pain/rash, non-truncal, or
              immunocompromised)</li>
            <li class="Herpes-Zoster">Aciclovir 800mg 5 times daily for 7 days</li>
          </ol>
        </ul>
        <ul class="General infectious">
          <li class="General infectious"><strong>Immediate antibiotics if:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li class="pediatric">Age &lt;6 months</li>
              <li>Severe symptoms (moderate-severe otalgia or fever
                &ge;39&deg;C)</li>
              <li class="ent">Otorrhea</li>
              <li class="ent pediatric">Bilateral AOM in children &lt;2 years</li>
              <li class="infectious">Immunocompromised</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li class="General pharmacology">Medication Review / Deprescribing
            (consider stopping unnecessary medications)</li>
          <li class="ent pharmacology"><strong>First-line antibiotic:</strong> <span
              class="pharmacology">Amoxicillin 40-45mg/kg/day PO divided BID
              (max 1g/dose) for 5-10 days</span></li>
          <li class="ent pharmacology"><strong>Penicillin allergy or recent
              amoxicillin use:</strong> <span class="pharmacology">Cefdinir
              14mg/kg/day PO divided QD-BID (max 600mg/day)</span></li>
          <li class="ent pharmacology"><strong>Treatment failure after 48-72h:</strong>
            <span class="pharmacology">Amoxicillin-clavulanate 45mg/kg/day PO
              divided BID (max 875mg/dose)</span></li>
        </ul>
        <ul class="ms cns">
          <li class="ms cns"><b>Multiple Sclerosis Management:</b>
            <ol>
              <li class="ms cns"><b>Acute Relapse:</b> High-dose steroids (e.g.,
                oral or IV Methylprednisolone).</li>
              <li class="ms cns"><b>Disease-Modifying Therapies (DMTs):</b> To
                be initiated and managed by Neurology specialist team.</li>
              <li><b>Symptom Management:</b>
                <ul>
                  <li class="ms cns">Spasticity (Baclofen, Gabapentin, Physio)</li>
                  <li class="ms cns">Neuropathic pain (Amitriptyline,
                    Gabapentin, Duloxetine)</li>
                  <li class="ms cns">Fatigue management (Amantadine, Modafinil -
                    specialist use)</li>
                  <li class="ms nephro">Bladder dysfunction (Oxybutynin,
                    intermittent self-catheterisation)</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </li>
          <ul class="chest-pain cvs emergency">
            <li class="chest-pain cvs"><b>Suspected ACS Protocol (MONA):</b></li>
            <ol>
              <li class="chest-pain cvs">Aspirin 300mg STAT (chewed or dispersed
                in water)</li>
              <li class="chest-pain cvs">Oxygen only if sats &lt;94%</li>
              <li class="chest-pain cvs">Nitrates (GTN) unless hypotensive/right
                ventricular MI</li>
              <li class="chest-pain cvs">Morphine for severe pain</li>
            </ol>
          </ul>
          <ul class="sinusitis ent cns">
            <li class="sinusitis ent cns"><b>Acute Sinusitis Management:</b></li>
            <ol>
              <li class="sinusitis ent cns">Reassurance that most cases are
                viral and self-limiting.</li>
              <li class="sinusitis ent cns">Analgesia (Paracetamol/Ibuprofen).</li>
              <li class="sinusitis ent cns">Intranasal saline or decongestants
                for short-term relief (max 7 days).</li>
              <li class="sinusitis ent cns pharmacology">Consider high-dose
                intranasal steroid spray (especially if allergic component).</li>
              <li class="sinusitis ent infectious cns pharmacology">Offer
                delayed/back-up antibiotic prescription. Immediate antibiotics
                only if systemically very unwell, high risk of complications, or
                symptoms are severe and prolonged (&gt;10 days).</li>
            </ol>
          </ul>
          <ul class="iih cns">
            <li class="iih cns"><b>Intracranial Hypertension Management:</b></li>
            <ol>
              <li class="iih cns general">Weight management is the cornerstone
                of long-term IIH treatment.</li>
              <li class="iih cns pharmacology"><b>First-line medication:</b>
                Acetazolamide (to reduce CSF production).</li>
              <li class="iih cns pharmacology"><b>Second-line options:</b>
                Topiramate (also aids weight loss/headache).</li>
              <li class="iih cns">Therapeutic lumbar puncture for temporary
                headache relief.</li>
            </ol>
          </ul>
          <ul class="OSA respiratory">
            <li class="OSA respiratory"><b>OSA Management:</b></li>
            <ol>
              <li class="OSA respiratory">Continuous Positive Airway Pressure
                (CPAP) therapy - Gold Standard</li>
              <li class="OSA respiratory">Mandibular Advancement Device (MAD) -
                for mild/moderate OSA or if CPAP intolerant</li>
            </ol>
          </ul>
          <ul class="headache cns">
            <li class="headache cns"><b>Headache Management:</b></li>
            <ol>
              <li class="headache cns"><b>Acute (Abortive) Treatment:</b>
                <ul>
                  <li class="headache cns">Migraine: Triptans (e.g.,
                    Sumatriptan) + NSAID or Paracetamol. Consider anti-emetics.</li>
                  <li class="headache cns">Tension-Type: Simple analgesia
                    (Aspirin, Paracetamol, or an NSAID).</li>
                  <li class="headache cns">Cluster: High-flow oxygen +
                    subcutaneous or nasal triptan.</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li><b>Prophylactic (Preventative) Treatment:</b>
                <ul>
                  <li class="headache cns">Offer if headaches are frequent or
                    significantly impacting quality of life.</li>
                  <li class="headache cns">Migraine options: Propranolol,
                    Topiramate, Amitriptyline.</li>
                  <li class="headache cns">Tension-Type options: Amitriptyline.</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li class="headache cns">Strongly advise against opiate use for
                primary headaches.</li>
            </ol>
            <li class="chest-pain cvs">Nitrates (GTN) unless hypotensive/right
              ventricular MI</li>
            <li class="chest-pain cvs">Morphine for severe pain</li>
          </ul>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ol>
    <ul>
      <li class="ortho-specific">Functional support (e.g., compression bandage,
        semi-rigid brace) for protected weight-bearing</li>
    </ul>
    <li class="General">Consent</li>
    <li class="General">Non-Medical:
      <ul class="General">
        <li class="ent">Warm compresses to affected ear</li>
        <li class="Herpes-Zoster">Keep rash clean and dry; cool compresses for
          comfort</li>
        <li class="General">As needed based on condition progression</li>
        <li class="cough">Review after therapeutic trial (e.g., PPI, inhalers)
          to assess response</li>
        <li class="palpitations cvs">Symptom diary to correlate with ambulatory
          ECG findings</li>
        <li class="respiratory">Smoking cessation counseling if applicable</li>
        <li class="sinusitis ent cns">Steam inhalation (with or without
          menthol/eucalyptus) for symptom relief</li>
        <li class="sinusitis ent cns">Nasal saline irrigation (e.g., Neti pot,
          saline sprays) to clear mucus and improve drainage</li>
        <li class="sinusitis ent cns">Stay well-hydrated to help thin mucus
          secretions</li>
        <li class="sinusitis ent cns">Use a humidifier to moisten dry indoor air</li>
        <li class="sinusitis ent cns">Sleep with head elevated to promote sinus
          drainage</li>
        <li class="sinusitis ent cns">Apply warm compresses to face to ease pain
          and promote drainage</li>
        <li class="chest-pain cvs">Lifestyle advice (diet, exercise) for
          secondary prevention of heart disease</li>
        <li class="SOB respiratory">Breathing control exercises, trigger
          avoidance (allergens, dust)</li>
        <li class="headache cns">Headache diary to identify triggers and
          patterns</li>
        <li class="pediatric">Breastfeeding support for infants (protective
          against AOM)</li>
        <li>General Practitioner (GP) for routine follow-up</li>
        <li class="palpitations cvs">Cardiology / Electrophysiology (for
          arrhythmia management)</li>
        <li class="PAD cvs surgery">Vascular Surgery Team</li>
        <li class="PAD cvs rehab">Podiatry / Chiropody for foot care</li>
        <li class="cough respiratory">Respiratory Medicine for persistent
          unexplained cough (&gt; 8 weeks)</li>
        <li class="General">Social Prescribing (referral to link workers,
          community groups)</li>
        <ol>
          <li class="General">&gt;65</li>
          <li class="General">psych patients</li>
          <li class="General">gynaec patients</li>
          <li class="General">abuse</li>
          <li class="General">etc</li>
        </ol>
        <li class="OSA General">Weight management advice (if overweight/obese)</li>
        <li class="OSA General">Positional therapy (e.g., avoiding supine sleep)</li>
        <li class="OSA General">Alcohol and sedative avoidance, especially
          before bedtime</li>
        <ul class="iih cns">
          <li class="iih cns"><b>IIH Lifestyle Management:</b></li>
          <ol>
            <li class="iih cns">Weight loss (5-10% of body weight can
              significantly improve symptoms)</li>
            <li class="iih cns">Low-sodium diet to help reduce fluid retention</li>
            <li class="iih cns">Adequate hydration (2-3L/day unless
              contraindicated)</li>
            <li class="iih cns">Sleep with head elevated (30-45 degrees) to
              reduce intracranial pressure at night</li>
            <li class="iih cns">Avoid activities that increase intra-abdominal
              pressure (heavy lifting, straining)</li>
            <li class="iih cns">Regular, moderate exercise (as tolerated and
              with medical clearance)</li>
            <li> bicycle insted of driving</li>
          </ol>
        </ul>
        <ul class="PAD cvs">
          <li class="PAD cvs"><b>PAD Lifestyle &amp; Self-Care:</b>
            <ol>
              <li class="PAD cvs respiratory">Smoking Cessation (critical)</li>
              <li class="PAD cvs respiratory">nicotine patch ok for pregnant
                women</li>
              <li class="PAD cvs respiratory">vernaculine and bupropion not for
                pregnant or breast feeding!</li>
              <li class="PAD cvs rehab">Supervised Exercise Programme (3 months)</li>
              <li class="PAD cvs">Meticulous foot care and hygiene advice
                (especially if diabetic)</li>
            </ol>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <ul class="ortho-specific">
          <li class="ortho-specific"><b>Sprain/Soft Tissue Injury Management:</b>
            <ol>
              <li class="ortho-specific">Structured PRICE/POLICE protocol advice
                (Protection, Optimal Loading, Rest, Ice, Compression, Elevation)</li>
              <li class="ortho-specific">Advise on practical details: e.g., Ice
                for 20 mins on, &gt;=1hr off; check compression tightness</li>
              <li class="ortho-specific">Promote early pain-limited movement and
                proprioceptive/balance exercises</li>
            </ol>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <ol class="General">
          <li class="General">Watch and wait!</li>
          <li class="General">Behavior diary</li>
          <li class="endocrine">Diabetes
            <ul class="endocrine">
              <li class="endocrine">food</li>
              <li class="endocrine"><a href="https://chatgpt.com/g/g-685ef36778488191a2d2704177c22a64-plab-2-feedback/c/6865ad97-b148-8007-94b7-f44171ebd0cf#:%7E:text=DAFNE%20%28%E2%80%9CDose%20Adjustment%20For%20Normal%20Eating%E2%80%9D%29">
                  DAFNE</a> ("Dose Adjustment For Normal Eating")</li>
              <li class="endocrine">Exercise</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li class="rheumatic">Chronic fatigue syndrome
            <ol class="rheumatic">
              <li class="rheumatic">CBT</li>
              <li class="rheumatic">Lifestyle</li>
              <li class="rheumatic">Not graded exercise</li>
            </ol>
          </li>
          <li class="hematology">Thalassemia minor
            <ol class="hematology">
              <li class="hematology">Counselling</li>
              <li class="hematology">Marriage counselling</li>
              <li class="hematology">Iron if severe</li>
            </ol>
          </li>
          <li class="nephro urology">Renal stones
            <ol class="nephro urology">
              <li class="nephro urology">Strainer for collecting Renal stones</li>
            </ol>
          </li>
          <li class="surgery">Surgical
            <ul class="surgery">
              <li>Complications</li>
              <ul>
                <li>Pain</li>
                <li>Damage</li>
                <li>bleeding</li>
                <li>infection</li>
                <li>Special</li>
              </ul>
              <li class="hematology">Stem cell transplant</li>
              <li class="hematology">Bone Marrow Transplant</li>
              <li class="surgery">Splenectomy
                <ul class="hematology">
                  <li class="hematology">ITP severe</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li class="surgery urology">Stent
                <ul class="urology">
                  <li class="nephro urology">Renal stones</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li class="surgery urology">PCNL (Percutaneous Nephrolithotomy)
                <ul class="urology">
                  <li class="nephro urology">Renal stones</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li class="derma">Can't do simple cosmetic procedures</li>
              <li class="derma">If lesions cause other problems then surgery</li>
              <ul class="PAD cvs surgery">
                <li class="PAD cvs surgery">Angioplasty +/- Stenting</li>
                <li class="PAD cvs surgery">Bypass Surgery</li>
                <li class="PAD cvs surgery">Amputation (for non-salvageable
                  limb)</li>
              </ul>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <ul class="palpitations cvs">
            <li class="palpitations cvs"><b>Palpitations Management:</b></li>
            <ol>
              <li class="palpitations cvs">Identify and manage triggers (e.g.,
                caffeine, alcohol, stress, lack of sleep)</li>
              <li class="palpitations cvs">Vagal manoeuvres for stable SVT (if
                appropriate and taught)</li>
              <li class="palpitations cvs">Consider Beta-blockers or
                Calcium-channel blockers for rate/symptom control</li>
              <li class="palpitations cvs emergency">Acute management of
                unstable tachycardia (as per ALS algorithm)</li>
            </ol>
          </ul>
          <ul class="PAD cvs">
            <li class="PAD cvs"><b>Peripheral Arterial Disease Management:</b></li>
            <ol>
              <li class="PAD cvs pharmacology">Antiplatelet: Clopidogrel 75mg OD
                (first-line)</li>
              <li class="PAD cvs pharmacology">Lipid modification: Atorvastatin
                80mg OD</li>
              <li class="PAD cvs pharmacology">Blood pressure control</li>
              <li class="PAD cvs pharmacology">Consider Naftidrofuryl oxalate
                for claudication if supervised exercise is
                ineffective/unsuitable</li>
            </ol>
          </ul>
          <ul class="cough respiratory">
            <li class="cough respiratory"><b>Cough Management:</b></li>
            <ol>
              <li class="cough">Acute Viral Cough (&lt; 3 weeks): Reassurance,
                hydration, honey/simple linctus. Advise against routine
                antibiotics.</li>
              <li class="cough respiratory">Suspected Pneumonia: Antibiotics
                based on local guidelines and CRB-65 score (e.g., Amoxicillin,
                Doxycycline).</li>
              <li class="cough git">Trial of PPI for 4-8 weeks if suspecting
                GORD-related cough.</li>
              <li class="cough ent">Trial of intranasal steroid spray if
                suspecting Upper Airway Cough Syndrome.</li>
            </ol>
          </ul>
          <li class="General">Patient Education
            <ul class="General">
              <li class="General">Warning Signs/Red Flags (Return immediately
                if):
                <ul class="General emergency">
                  <li class="headache cns emergency">"Thunderclap" headache
                    (peaks in severity within a minute)</li>
                  <li class="headache cns emergency">New onset neurological
                    deficit (weakness, vision loss, speech difficulty)</li>
                  <li class="headache cns emergency">New headache in patients
                    &gt;50, or with a history of cancer or immunosuppression</li>
                  <li class="headache cns emergency">Headache with fever, neck
                    stiffness, photophobia, and rash (Meningitis)</li>
                  <li class="headache rheumatic emergency">Symptoms of GCA: jaw
                    claudication, visual disturbance, scalp tenderness</li>
                  <li class="cns emergency">Facial weakness or asymmetry</li>
                  <li class="sinusitis ent cns emergency">Severe headache or
                    facial pain not responding to analgesia</li>
                  <li class="sinusitis ent cns emergency">Visual changes (double
                    vision, vision loss, impaired eye movements)</li>
                  <li class="sinusitis ent cns emergency">Periorbital swelling,
                    erythema, or proptosis (bulging eye)</li>
                  <li class="sinusitis ent cns emergency">Signs of meningitis
                    (severe headache, neck stiffness, photophobia, rash)</li>
                  <li class="sinusitis ent cns emergency">Focal neurological
                    signs (e.g., cranial nerve palsies, altered mental status)</li>
                  <li class="iih cns emergency ophthalmology">New or worsening
                    vision changes (blurred vision, double vision, vision loss)</li>
                  <li class="iih cns emergency">Severe, persistent headache not
                    responding to analgesia</li>
                  <li class="iih cns emergency">New onset pulsatile tinnitus
                    (whooshing sound in ears)</li>
                  <li class="iih cns emergency">New neurological symptoms
                    (nausea, vomiting, dizziness)</li>
                  <li class="ent emergency">Worsening pain or fever after 48h of
                    antibiotics</li>
                  <li class="ent emergency">Signs of mastoiditis (post-auricular
                    swelling, erythema, or tenderness)</li>
                  <li class="ent cns emergency">Dizziness, vertigo, or nystagmus</li>
                </ul>
                <ul class="ms cns emergency">
                  <li class="ms cns"><b>MS Red Flags (Contact MS Nurse/Seek
                      urgent review if):</b></li>
                  <ol>
                    <li class="ms cns">New neurological symptoms lasting &gt; 24
                      hours (suggests relapse).</li>
                    <li class="ms cns">Signs of severe infection (especially if
                      on immunosuppressive DMTs).</li>
                    <li class="ms cns">Sudden, severe worsening of spasticity or
                      pain.</li>
                  </ol>
                </ul>
                <ul class="SOB respiratory emergency">
                  <li class="SOB"><b>Shortness of Breath Red Flags (Call 999):</b></li>
                  <ol>
                    <li class="SOB">Inability to speak in full sentences</li>
                    <li class="SOB">Using accessory muscles to breathe
                      (neck/shoulders pulling in)</li>
                    <li class="SOB cns">New confusion, drowsiness, or dizziness</li>
                    <li class="SOB cvs">Cyanosis (blue lips or fingers)</li>
                    <li class="SOB">Silent chest (in a known asthmatic)</li>
                  </ol>
                </ul>
                <ul class="chest-pain cvs emergency">
                  <li class="chest-pain cvs"><b>Chest Pain Red Flags (Call 999):</b></li>
                  <ol>
                    <li class="chest-pain cvs">Central crushing/heavy chest pain
                      lasting &gt; 15 mins</li>
                    <li class="chest-pain cvs">Pain radiating to neck, jaw,
                      shoulders, or one/both arms</li>
                    <li class="chest-pain cvs">Associated symptoms: shortness of
                      breath, sweating, nausea, light-headedness</li>
                  </ol>
                </ul>
                <ul class="OSA respiratory emergency">
                  <li class="OSA"><b>OSA Red Flags (Seek urgent review if):</b></li>
                  <ol>
                    <li class="OSA cns">Excessive daytime sleepiness causing
                      accidents or near-misses (e.g., while driving)</li>
                    <li class="OSA cns">Severe morning headaches, confusion, or
                      irritability</li>
                    <li class="OSA cvs">Signs of right heart failure (e.g., new
                      leg swelling)</li>
                  </ol>
                </ul>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </ul>
      <ul class="Herpes-Zoster infectious emergency">
        <li class="Herpes-Zoster"><b>Herpes Zoster Red Flags:</b></li>
        <ol>
          <li class="Herpes-Zoster ophthalmology">Any eye symptoms (redness,
            pain, vision change) - immediate review needed</li>
          <li class="Herpes-Zoster cns">New facial droop, hearing loss, or
            severe vertigo (Ramsay Hunt)</li>
          <li class="Herpes-Zoster derma">Signs of bacterial superinfection
            (spreading redness, pus)</li>
        </ol>
      </ul>
      <ul class="ortho-specific emergency">
        <li class="ortho-specific"><b>Musculoskeletal Red Flags:</b></li>
        <ol>
          <li class="ortho-specific">Worsening pain/swelling after 48-72h</li>
          <li class="ortho-specific">Inability to bear weight</li>
          <li class="ortho-specific">New numbness or change in limb colour</li>
          <li class="ortho-specific emergency cvs">Calf pain or swelling (DVT
            risk)</li>
          <li class="ortho-specific infectious">Fever</li>
        </ol>
      </ul>
      <ul class="palpitations cvs emergency">
        <li class="palpitations cvs"><b>Palpitations Red Flags (Call 999/Seek
            immediate help):</b></li>
        <ol>
          <li class="palpitations cvs">Palpitations associated with syncope
            (fainting) or pre-syncope</li>
          <li class="palpitations cvs">Associated chest pain or severe shortness
            of breath</li>
          <li class="palpitations cvs">If palpitations feel very fast AND
            irregular</li>
        </ol>
      </ul>
      <ul class="PAD cvs emergency">
        <li class="PAD cvs"><b>Peripheral Arterial Disease Red Flags:</b></li>
        <ol>
          <li class="PAD cvs">Development of rest pain (pain in feet at night)</li>
          <li class="PAD cvs">New ulcers, black areas, or non-healing wounds on
            feet/toes</li>
          <li class="PAD cvs">Sudden onset of a cold, painful, pale limb (Acute
            Limb Ischaemia - call 999)</li>
        </ol>
      </ul>
      <ul class="cough respiratory emergency">
        <li class="cough respiratory"><b>Cough Red Flags (Seek urgent review
            if):</b></li>
        <ol>
          <li class="cough hematology">Coughing up blood (hemoptysis)</li>
          <li class="cough oncology">Unexplained weight loss, drenching night
            sweats</li>
          <li class="cough respiratory">Associated shortness of breath, chest
            pain, or wheeze</li>
          <li class="cough ent">Hoarseness lasting &gt; 3 weeks</li>
          <li class="cough">A "whooping" or "barking" sound</li>
        </ol>
      </ul>
    </li>
    <ul class="General">
      <li class="ms cns"><b>DVLA (Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency)
          Notification:</b>
        <ul class="ms cns">
          <li class="ms cns">MS is a notifiable condition to the DVLA if it
            affects driving ability</li>
          <li class="ms cns">Patients must inform the DVLA if they experience
            symptoms that could affect their driving</li>
          <li class="ms cns">Driving may be permitted if symptoms are
            well-controlled and don't affect driving ability</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li class="rheumatic">Giant cell arteritis
        <ol class="rheumatic">
          <li class="rheumatic ophthalmology">Vision disturbances</li>
          <li class="rheumatic">Headache</li>
        </ol>
      </li>
      <li class="headache cns"><b>DVLA (Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency)
          Notification:</b>
        <ul class="headache cns">
          <li class="headache cns">Advise re: driving if migraine with aura or
            cluster headaches affect vision or awareness</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li class="General">Emergency Contacts:
        <ol class="General">
          <li class="emergency">999 - emergency</li>
          <li class="emergency">112 - emergency</li>
          <li class="General">111 - non emergency</li>
          <li class="oncology">2-wk-wait coordinator - Cancer</li>
          <li class="psychiatric">111-2 - mental health</li>
          <li class="psychiatric">0300 123 1100 - Acas Helpline</li>
          <li class="psychiatric">116 123 Samaritans</li>
          <li class="cns">SUDEP (Sudden Unexpected Death in Epilepsy)</li>
        </ol>
      </li>
      <li class="Herpes-Zoster infectious">Contagiousness: Advise that rash can
        transmit chickenpox to non-immune contacts; keep covered</li>
      <li class="derma">Mole &rarr; melanoma
        <ul class="derma">
          <li class="derma">ABCDE assessment</li>
          <li class="derma">Urgent referral if suspicious</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li class="nephro cvs">Hyperkalemia - ACE, ARBs, Spironolactone
        <ul class=" nephro cvs">
          <li class="cvs">Don't take K+ supplements</li>
          <li class="cvs">Muscle weakness, cramps or floppiness</li>
          <li class="cvs">Tingling or pins and needles</li>
          <li class="cvs">Palpitations, chest heaviness or dizziness</li>
          <li class="cvs">Feeling unusually tired or short of breath</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <li class="General cns endocrine cvs">DVLA (Driver and Vehicle Licensing
      Agency) Notification</li>
    <ul>
      <li class="ortho-specific">Counsel on driving safety (must be able to
        perform emergency stop)</li>
      <li class="chest-pain cvs">Advise on driving restrictions post-MI, stent,
        etc.</li>
      <li class="SOB">Advise on driving restrictions for conditions causing
        sudden disabling breathlessness</li>
      <li class="PAD cvs">Advise re: driving if claudication pain is distracting
        or limiting</li>
      <li class="palpitations cvs">Advise on driving restrictions for
        arrhythmias causing or likely to cause incapacity</li>
      <li class="OSA cns emergency">Mandatory DVLA notification for OSA - must
        stop driving until symptoms are controlled with treatment</li>
      <li class="iih cns">Mandatory DVLA notification for IIH - must stop
        driving if vision is affected or if experiencing episodes of visual
        disturbance</li>
      <li class="Herpes-Zoster">Advise re: driving if ophthalmic involvement or
        on sedating medication for pain</li>
    </ul>
    <li class="General cns endocrine cvs">Heavy machinery</li>
    <li class="General">Educational materials provided:
      <ul class="General">
        <li class="General">Leaflets
          <ol class="General">
            <li class="General">QR code for online</li>
            <li class="derma">British Association of Dermatologists (BAD)
              leaflets</li>
            <li class="respiratory SOB">Asthma + Lung UK / British Lung
              Foundation materials</li>
            <li class="cardiology chest-pain cvs">British Heart Foundation
              resources</li>
            <li class="ent">British Tinnitus Association (Tinnitus UK) leaflet</li>
          </ol>
        </li>
        <li class="ortho-specific">Provide patient with written self-care
          leaflet/copy of plan for their injury</li>
        <li class="SOB respiratory">Personalised Asthma/COPD Action Plan</li>
        <li class="General">Personalised Care Plan (written summary of
          consultation)</li>
        <li class="General">Pamphlets</li>
        <li class="General">Websites and apps</li>
      </ul>
    </li>
    <li class="General">Useful resources/links:
      <ul class="General">
        <li class="General">NHS Choices</li>
        <li class="General">Patient.co.uk</li>
        <li class="General">Condition-specific charities and support groups</li>
        <li class="Herpes-Zoster cns">The Shingles Support Society</li>
      </ul>
    </li>
    <li class="General">Follow Up
      <ul class="General">
        <li class="General">Type:
          <ul class="General">
            <li class="General">telephone</li>
            <li class="General">in person</li>
            <li class="General">home visit</li>
            <li class="General">other</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li class="General">Frequency:
          <ul class="General">
            <li class="ent">If symptoms worsen or persist &gt;48h on antibiotics</li>
            <li class="ent pediatric">Routine follow-up in 2-4 weeks if
              recurrent AOM or concern for hearing/developmental issues</li>
            <li class="ortho-specific">Specify criteria for review (e.g.,
              persistent pain, instability, failure to improve by expected
              timeline)</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li class="General">Monitoring
          <ul class="General">
            <li class="ent">Resolution of fever and pain within 48-72h of
              treatment</li>
            <li class="OSA ent">CPAP compliance and efficacy data monitoring</li>
            <li class="OSA cns ent">Improvement in Epworth Sleepiness Scale
              score</li>
            <li class="OSA cvs ent">Blood pressure monitoring</li>
            <li class="Herpes-Zoster cns">Monitor for development/severity of
              Post-Herpetic Neuralgia (PHN)</li>
            <li class="SOB respiratory">Monitor symptom control, peak flow,
              inhaler use</li>
            <li class="ent pediatric">Hearing assessment if speech/language
              delay or recurrent AOM</li>
            <li class="ent">TM mobility and appearance at follow-up</li>
            <li class="iih cns">Regular visual field testing (baseline and every
              3-6 months initially)</li>
            <li class="iih cns">Optic nerve head assessment (fundoscopy or OCT)
              at each visit</li>
            <li class="iih cns">Headache diary to monitor frequency, severity,
              and response to treatment</li>
            <li class="iih cns">Weight and BMI tracking at each visit</li>
            <li class="iih cns">Medication side effects monitoring (especially
              for acetazolamide and topiramate)</li>
            <li class="iih cns">Assessment of quality of life and functional
              impact</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li class="General">Specialist referrals:
          <ul class="General">
            <li class="ent">ENT referral for recurrent AOM (&ge;3 episodes in 6
              months or &ge;4 in 12 months)</li>
            <li class="ent audiology">Consider audiology referral if persistent
              hearing loss or speech delay</li>
            <li class="ortho-specific rehab">Clear pathway to physiotherapy
              (referral or self-referral info)</li>
            <li class="chest-pain cvs">Rapid Access Chest Pain Clinic</li>
            <li class="Herpes-Zoster cns">Referral to pain clinic for
              persistent/severe PHN</li>
            <li class="OSA respiratory ent">Sleep Clinic / Respiratory team</li>
            <li class="OSA ent">ENT referral if anatomical obstruction suspected
              (e.g., large tonsils)</li>
            <li class="ms cns">Neurology referral for confirmed or suspected MS</li>
            <li class="ms cns">MS Specialist Nurse referral for ongoing support
              and management</li>
            <li class="iih cns">Urgent Neurology and Ophthalmology referral for
              all new IIH diagnoses</li>
            <li class="iih cns">Consider referral to Neuro-ophthalmology for
              complex cases</li>
            <li class="headache cns">Neurology or specialist Headache Clinic for
              refractory or difficult-to-diagnose headaches</li>
            <li class="SOB respiratory">Respiratory nurse specialist / Community
              respiratory team</li>
            <li class="SOB cvs">Heart failure nurse specialist team</li>
            <li class="General">Clear communication/handover to receiving team
              (e.g., SBAR format)</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li class="General">Allied health:
          <ul class="General">
            <li class="rehab"><b>Occupational Therapist</b></li>
            <li class="rehab"><u>Physiotherapist</u></li>
            <li class="SOB rehab respiratory">Respiratory Physiotherapist</li>
            <li class="rehab">Dietitian</li>
            <li class="psychiatric">Mental Health Support / IAPT</li>
            <li class="chest-pain cvs">Cardiac Rehabilitation Team</li>
            <li class="SOB respiratory">Pulmonary Rehabilitation</li>
            <li class="ms cns rehab">Neuro-physiotherapist (specialized in MS)</li>
            <li class="ms cns">Continence Advisor</li>
            <li class="ms cns rehab">Occupational Therapist (specialized in MS)</li>
            <li class="ms cns">MS Specialist Nurse (if not already referred)</li>
            <li class="iih cns">Dietitian (for weight management support)</li>
            <li class="iih cns">Ophthalmology specialist nurse (for visual field
              monitoring)</li>
            <li class="iih cns">Pain management team (for chronic headache
              management if needed)</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </li>
    <li class="General">Consider mandatory reporting duties (e.g., notifiable
      diseases)
